{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 20:02:37.683084", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnostic Report — Clos Lab (EBGP)\\nDate: (current capture)\\n\\n1) Executive summary\\n- The control plane (FRR/BGP) and router forwarding appear healthy: all FRR routers have established EBGP sessions and the expected /24 host prefixes are present in router RIBs.\\n- There is significant, localized packet loss affecting host 10.0.0.2 (pc_0_0). Multiple other hosts experience 25–75% packet loss when pinging pc_0_0; some probes returned no result.\\n- Root cause evidence points to an artificial link impairment on pc_0_0: netem qdisc on pc_0_0 shows \"corrupt 60%\", i.e., a 60% packet corruption injection is configured on pc_0_0’s egress. This explains the intermittent/partial connectivity to that host.\\n\\n2) High-level health assessment\\n- BGP status: healthy. All expected EBGP neighbors are UP on:\\n  - super_spine_router_0 (AS65000): peers with spine routers\\n  - spine_router_0_0 (AS65100) and spine_router_0_1 (AS65101): peers with super-spine and leaves\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (AS65200) and leaf_router_0_1 (AS65201): peers with spines\\n  - show ip bgp summary on each router shows established sessions and prefixes exchanged.\\n- Routing: each leaf has its /24 connected and BGP routes for other /24s are present in router RIBs (routes point to appropriate inter-router /31 nexthops).\\n- Data-plane: degraded for traffic destined to 10.0.0.2 (pc_0_0); other hosts and inter-router links show no broad data-plane failure.\\n\\n3) Observed anomalies (evidence)\\n- Reachability/ping failure patterns (selected examples from reachability test):\\n  - pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0: 75% loss (tx=4, rx=1)\\n  - pc_0_2 -> pc_0_0: 50% loss (tx=4, rx=2)\\n  - pc_0_3 -> pc_0_0: 75% loss (tx=4, rx=1)\\n  - pc_1_0 -> pc_0_0: 50% loss\\n  - pc_1_1 -> pc_0_0: 25% loss\\n  - pc_1_3 -> pc_0_0: probe status unknown (no result)\\n  - Summary: multiple sources show non-trivial packet loss specifically to 10.0.0.2.\\n- Host/interface state:\\n  - pc_0_0 ifconfig: eth0 up, IP 10.0.0.2/24, default gw 10.0.0.1.\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 ifconfig: eth4 is 10.0.0.1/24 (correct gateway), routes and interface counters look normal (only 1 dropped RX reported).\\n- qdisc / traffic control evidence:\\n  - pc_0_0: \"qdisc netem ... corrupt 60%\" — netem configured with 60% corruption. (Observed output: qdisc netem ... corrupt 60%).\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (eth4): fq_codel shows no drops and normal counters.\\n- BGP/FRR evidence:\\n  - leaf_router_0_0: show ip bgp summary — all 4 spine neighbors established, prefixes received.\\n  - spine and super-spine routers: sessions up, prefixes present, routes to 10.0.0.0/24 installed.\\n\\n4) Localization — likely faulty device(s)\\n- Primary faulty device: pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2).\\n  - Rationale: packet loss is concentrated toward this host, and the host itself shows a netem qdisc configured to corrupt 60% of packets — a direct and sufficient explanation.\\n- Network devices (leaf/spine/super-spine routers): no evidence of BGP/session failures or interface errors across routers; routing to the 10.0.0.0/24 prefix is present and correctly advertised. Leaf router (10.0.0.1) shows expected connected route.\\n\\n5) Root-cause analysis\\n- Direct cause: QoS/traffic-control impairment on pc_0_0. The netem qdisc on pc_0_0 is configured with \"corrupt 60%\" which will randomly corrupt (and effectively drop/unusable) roughly 60% of packets at the host’s egress/ingress depending on placement. This produces the observed asymmetric/intermittent packet loss when other hosts ping pc_0_0.\\n- Contributing factors: none observed in the routing/control plane — BGP and inter-router links are stable and routes point correctly, so the impairment is local to the host.\\n\\n6) Confidence level\\n- High confidence that pc_0_0’s netem corruption is the root cause of the observed packet loss. Evidence: direct tc/netem output showing corrupt 60% plus consistent ping-loss patterns to that specific IP, while router BGP and link counters are normal.\\n\\n7) Relevant raw findings (excerpts)\\n- Reachability: multiple hosts report 25–75% packet loss when targeting 10.0.0.2 (pc_0_0).\\n- pc_0_0 tc/qdisc: \"qdisc netem ... corrupt 60%\".\\n- leaf_router_0_0 ip route: 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected on eth4 (10.0.0.1).\\n- FRR BGP summaries: all EBGP neighbors are established and advertising prefixes (no flaps or session issues observed).\\n\\n8) Suggested next diagnostic confirmations (no mitigation)\\n- (If desired) run ping/traceroute from pc_0_0 toward multiple peers to characterize whether corruption affects egress, ingress, or both (to confirm directional behavior).\\n- Inspect full tc qdisc configuration on pc_0_0 (tc qdisc show dev eth0) and any scripts that apply netem to determine why corruption was applied.\\n- Gather packet captures at leaf_router_0_0 (eth4) and on pc_0_0 to confirm corrupted packets and check for retransmissions/ICMP errors.\\n\\nEnd of report., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='0538031c-2285-43f0-bde5-61eec6722d32'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
